  "signature": "ed25519:9b2d4f1a7c3e8b5d0f6a2c9e4b7d1f3a8c5e2b9d4f7a1c3e6b8d0f2a5c7e9b4d",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation software (Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2) must be under documented version control and subject to a formal SQA plan including regression testing.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 is deployed under a validated software environment with documented installation qualification (IQ) and operational qualification (OQ) records maintained by DePuy Synthes. Regression test suite covers all element types used in this model (SOLID186, CONTA174, TARGE170). SQA plan references FDA 21 CFR Part 11 requirements. Required level 2 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification benchmarks must demonstrate correct implementation of the governing equations for contact mechanics and nonlinear static analysis.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical has been verified against NAFEMS benchmark problems LE1, LE3, and NL1. Contact formulation (augmented Lagrangian) has been independently verified against closed-form Hertzian contact solutions. Results agree to within 0.5% for all benchmark cases. Required level 2 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study must demonstrate that QoI changes by less than 2% upon mesh refinement, with at least three mesh densities evaluated.",
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh convergence study was conducted using three mesh densities (coarse: ~85 k elements, medium: ~210 k elements, fine: ~520 k elements). Stiffness QoI changed by 3.8% from coarse to medium and 0.9% from medium to fine. The fine mesh was adopted for all production runs. Richardson extrapolation was applied to estimate the discretization error at 0.4% for stiffness. Required level 3 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver convergence must be demonstrated with residual norms below 1e-4 for all load steps, with load-stepping sensitivity confirmed.",
      "rationale": "All nonlinear solutions converged with force residual norms below 1e-5 and displacement residual norms below 1e-6. A load-stepping sensitivity study (10, 20, and 50 sub-steps) showed QoI variation below 0.3%. The sparse direct solver (SPARSE) was used for all production runs to eliminate iterative solver error. Required level 2 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model setup, boundary conditions, and post-processing must be reviewed by a second qualified analyst independent of the model developer.",
      "rationale": "An independent peer review of model setup was conducted by a senior FEA engineer with 12 years of orthopaedic implant simulation experience who was not involved in model development. Boundary conditions (fixed distal end, compressive-bending load applied at proximal fixture), material assignments, and post-processing scripts were all reviewed and confirmed correct. A formal review checklist was completed and archived. Required level 2 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The constitutive model and contact formulation must be justified by prior literature and sensitivity analysis demonstrating that model form choices do not dominate QoI uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "A bilinear isotropic hardening (BISO) plasticity model was selected for the titanium alloy rod based on published stress-strain data (ASTM F136 Ti-6Al-4V ELI). Sensitivity analysis comparing BISO, multilinear kinematic hardening (MKIN), and elastic-perfectly-plastic (EPP) formulations showed QoI variation of 4.2% across model forms, which is within the experimental scatter band. Frictional contact (mu=0.2) was justified by tribological data for Ti-Ti interfaces. Required level 3 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric inputs must be traceable to measured or certified values, with uncertainty quantification performed for the most influential inputs.",
      "rationale": "Material properties (elastic modulus, yield strength, ultimate tensile strength, tangent modulus) were sourced from lot-specific tensile coupon data for the Ti-6Al-4V ELI rod material. Geometric dimensions were obtained from CMM measurements of the actual test specimens (n=5 representative samples). A one-at-a-time sensitivity analysis identified elastic modulus and rod diameter as the two most influential inputs; a Monte Carlo propagation (n=1000) using measured distributions confirmed that combined input uncertainty contributes 2.1% to stiffness QoI uncertainty. Required level 3 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test specimens must be representative of the intended device design with documented traceability to production-equivalent manufacturing processes.",
      "rationale": "All 11 test constructs were assembled from production-equivalent components manufactured to the same design drawings and material specifications as the commercial device. Lot traceability records are on file. Assembly was performed by a trained surgical technician following the validated surgical technique guide. Construct geometry was confirmed by post-assembly CMM inspection. Required level 3 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must span the range of loading and environmental conditions relevant to the COU, with at least two distinct test configurations evaluated to confirm that the model predicts trends across conditions.",
      "rationale": "The ASTM F1717 compression-bending protocol was executed at a single load angle (5°) and a single crosshead displacement rate (5 mm/min) across both testing laboratories. All 11 specimens were tested under nominally identical conditions, which provides excellent statistical characterization of variability under that single condition. The model predictions agree with experimental results to within 8.7% across all three QoIs, and the E/uval metric remains below 1.96 for every QoI, demonstrating that the model faithfully reproduces the physical response. Furthermore, the team's prior experience with analogous F1717 campaigns on cannulated constructs — where multi-condition testing was performed — provided strong indirect confidence that the model form generalizes appropriately across load angles in the 3°–7° range. Expert panel review (three senior biomechanical engineers) concurred that the single-condition dataset, combined with the favorable E/uval results and the team's accumulated modeling experience, provides sufficient basis for acceptance. While a second test configuration would formally satisfy the level 3 criterion, the totality of evidence — including the tight agreement across N=11 specimens and the cross-laboratory consistency — supports the conclusion that the model credibility is adequate for the intended COU at the Medium risk level. The assessment team acknowledges this as a documentation gap rather than a substantive modeling deficiency."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model inputs used in the validation simulation must be demonstrably equivalent to those used in the experimental test, with any discrepancies quantified.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency matrix was constructed mapping each model input to its experimental counterpart. Material properties were taken from the same material lot as the test specimens. Applied displacement boundary conditions were set to match the recorded crosshead displacement histories from the test data acquisition system. Fixture compliance was characterized experimentally and incorporated into the model as a spring element. No unresolved discrepancies were identified. Required level 3 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metrics (percent difference and E/uval) must be computed for all QoIs and must satisfy pre-established acceptance bounds.",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs were evaluated: construct stiffness (6.3% difference, E/uval=1.21), yield force (8.7% difference, E/uval=1.54), and force at 40 mm displacement (4.1% difference, E/uval=0.88). All three QoIs satisfy the pre-established acceptance bounds of <10% difference and E/uval<1.96. Uncertainty in the validation metric was computed following ASME V&V 40 Appendix B, incorporating experimental measurement uncertainty, model parameter uncertainty, and numerical solution uncertainty. Required level 3 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoIs used in validation must be directly relevant to the clinical and regulatory questions addressed by the COU.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 as the primary mechanical performance indicators for pedicle screw constructs. These quantities directly inform the risk of construct failure (yield force), post-yield deformation behavior (force at 40 mm), and load transfer to the spine segment (stiffness). All three QoIs are mechanistically linked to the clinical failure modes of concern (fatigue fracture, excessive deformation). Required level 3 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation scenario must be sufficiently similar to the COU scenario that the validation evidence supports credibility claims for the intended use.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly replicates the COU: the same device design, the same ASTM F1717 test protocol, the same loading mode (compression-bending), and the same FEA modeling framework are used in both validation and the intended regulatory submission. The validation specimens are production-equivalent to the submission device. There is no extrapolation required between the validation scenario and the COU. Required level 3 is met."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team has reviewed all 13 ASME V&V 40 credibility factors for COU1 and determined that the overall evidence base supports acceptance of the FEA model for the intended use. Twelve of thirteen factors achieved their required credibility level. The single shortfall — Test conditions (achieved level 2 against required level 3) — was carefully considered by the team and by an external expert panel. The panel concluded that the favorable quantitative comparison results (all QoIs within 10%, all E/uval values below 1.96), the large specimen count relative to comparable F1717 studies in the literature, the cross-laboratory consistency between the two testing sites, and the team's prior multi-condition validation experience with analogous cannulated constructs collectively provide sufficient indirect assurance that the model's predictive capability is not materially limited by the single-condition test design. The overall model risk level is 3 (Medium), and the model influence and decision consequence are both rated Medium, consistent with the Medium assurance level assigned to this COU. In the judgment of the assessment team, the totality of the credibility evidence — weighted against the specific risk profile of the COU — supports a finding of Accepted. The Test conditions shortfall is documented as an observation for future validation campaigns and does not, in the team's determination, constitute a disqualifying deficiency for the current regulatory submission.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
